{"id":"1807.02990","submitter":"H\\'ector Mart\\'inez-Rodr\\'iguez","authors":"H\\'ector Mart\\'inez-Rodr\\'iguez, Carles Badenes, Shiu-Hang Lee, Daniel\n  J. Patnaude, Adam R. Foster, Hiroya Yamaguchi, Katie Auchettl, Eduardo Bravo,\n  Patrick O. Slane, Anthony L. Piro, Sangwook Park, Shigehiro Nagataki","title":"Chandrasekhar and sub-Chandrasekhar models for the X-ray emission of\n  Type Ia supernova remnants (I): Bulk properties","comments":"22 pages, 14 figures, published in the ApJ","journal-ref":"The Astrophysical Journal, 865:151 (16pp), 2018 October 1","doi":"10.3847/1538-4357/aadaec","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Type Ia supernovae originate from the explosion of carbon-oxygen white dwarfs\nin binary systems, but the exact nature of their progenitors remains elusive.\nThe bulk properties of Type Ia supernova remnants, such as the radius and the\ncentroid energy of the Fe K$\\alpha$ blend in the X-ray spectrum, are determined\nby the properties of the supernova ejecta and the ambient medium. We model the\ninteraction between Chandrasekhar and sub-Chandrasekhar models for Type Ia\nsupernova ejecta and a range of uniform ambient medium densities in one\ndimension up to an age of 5000 years. We generate synthetic X-ray spectra from\nthese supernova remnant models and compare their bulk properties at different\nexpansion ages with X-ray observations from \\textit{Chandra} and\n\\textit{Suzaku}. We find that our models can successfully reproduce the bulk\nproperties of most observed remnants, suggesting that Type Ia SN progenitors do\nnot modify their surroundings significantly on scales of a few pc. Ambient\nmedium density and expansion age are the main contributors to the diversity of\nthe bulk properties in our models. Chandrasekhar and sub-Chandrasekhar\nprogenitors make similar predictions for the bulk remnant properties, but\ndetailed fits to X-ray spectra have the power to discriminate explosion\nenergetics and progenitor scenarios.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 Jul 2018 08:57:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 4 Oct 2018 02:29:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-10-17"}
{"id":"1807.02991","submitter":"Martin Helmer","authors":"Elisenda Feliu and Martin Helmer","title":"Multistationarity and Bistability for Fewnomial Chemical Reaction\n  Networks","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Bulletin of Mathematical Biology, 2018","doi":"10.1007/s11538-018-00555-z","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG cs.SC math.DS q-bio.MN q-bio.QM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Bistability and multistationarity are properties of reaction networks linked\nto switch-like responses and connected to cell memory and cell decision making.\nDetermining whether and when a network exhibits bistability is a hard and open\nmathematical problem. One successful strategy consists of analyzing small\nnetworks and deducing that some of the properties are preserved upon passage to\nthe full network. Motivated by this we study chemical reaction networks with\nfew chemical complexes. Under mass-action kinetics the steady states of these\nnetworks are described by fewnomial systems, that is polynomial systems having\nfew distinct monomials. Such systems of polynomials are often studied in real\nalgebraic geometry by the use of Gale dual systems. Using this Gale duality we\ngive precise conditions in terms of the reaction rate constants for the number\nand stability of the steady states of families of reaction networks with one\nnon-flow reaction.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 Jul 2018 08:58:05 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 3 Dec 2018 17:12:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-12-20"}
